    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="863"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d863">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/766</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Helsingfors</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HT2"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Haynes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d863fn1">Repeated to the Ambassador in Russia in telegram
                        No. 1890, Dec. 8, 5 p.m., with instructions: “Advise Department your views
                        fully and at earliest opportunity.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsingfors</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 6, 11.10
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The president Finland Senate to-day before Diet proclaimed Finland free republic.
                    He asks me to ascertain if the United States of America will recognize Finland
                    as independent state and if so may government send delegates to lay their point
                    of view before our Government.<note n="2" xml:id="d863fn2">Answered Dec. 8:
                        “Matter under consideration.”</note> I learn from reliable sources that
                    Swedish-Germans [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>] urging Germany immediately to
                    recognize Finland independence. Only our prompt recognition will prevent Germany
                    from securing firm sympathy and domination in eastern Baltic. Names of delegates
                    will be referred to me for approval. After having consulted French and English
                    colleagues they are dispatching similar wires to their Governments and
                    Embassies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HT2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Thornwell Haynes</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
